article.headline: Dominance of Silver Stars continues
article.linkText: Second-half surge from Bird, Jackson powers Storm
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- All-Stars Sue Bird and Lauren Jackson laughed and
smiled, enjoying a blowout victory for the first time since early
in the season.

The duo combined for all 15 points during a decisive second half
run, and the Seattle Storm beat the San Antonio Silver Stars 92-70
Friday night.

It was Seattle's third win in its last 10 games, and its
second-largest margin of victory this year. Seattle beat the Silver
Stars by 28 on May 29.

"We did have a lot of fun out there," Bird said. "We know
that when we're having fun and playing hard, we can win that way."

Bird and Jackson scored 32 of Seattle's 50 second-half points,
as the Storm made a season-high 11 3-pointers. It tied for the
second-most 3-pointers made in franchise history. Seattle made 13
against Los Angeles on July 11, 2002.

"When they have those two elements going, they're in pretty
good shape," San Antonio coach Dan Hughes said.

Seattle (9-10) led by seven early in the second half, but a
jumper from Marie Ferdinand pulled the Silver Stars (5-15) to 52-51
with 12:41 left.

Jackson scored at the other end to put Seattle up three, the
start of a 15-4 run. Bird drew an offensive foul on Shannon Johnson
that erased a basket, and then hit consecutive 3-pointers to give
Seattle a 60-51 lead.

Bird finally capped the run with a three-point play that gave
the Storm a 67-55 lead with 9:31 left. San Antonio could not stop
the momentum as Seattle scored 14 of the next 20 and built a
20-point lead.

"Sue came out and just broke it wide open," Seattle coach Anne
Donovan said. "Lauren was setting some tremendous screens for her
to get open and frankly they didn't know what to do with it."

Jackson finished with a game-high 27 points for Seattle, and
grabbed nine rebounds. Bird scored 14 of her 19 points in the
second half, Betty Lennox added 15 and Janell Burse scored 10 of
her 12 in the first half for the Storm.

It was Seattle's first win since beating Sacramento 74-67 on
July 3. The Storm lost six of their previous seven, including a
78-71 setback to Washington on Wednesday.

"I haven't been able to hit the side of a brickhouse for the
past ... ever," said Jackson, who made 9 of 15 shots, and three
3-pointers. "It felt good, like I was starting to get my rhythm
back."

San Antonio, which lost Thursday afternoon at Sacramento,
dropped its third straight. The Silver Stars are 1-10 on the road,
and 0-7 in the Western Conference. The Silver Stars' lone road win
came June 23 at Charlotte -- the only team with a worse record.

Rookie Katie Feenstra scored a season-high 17 for San Antonio.
Ferdinand also had 17 points and Johnson finished with 10.

Seattle's second-half surge made up for a missed opportunity in
the first half. The Storm went on an 18-8 run to build a 34-24
advantage, but San Antonio stemmed the momentum and cut the lead to
42-37 at halftime.

"It was disappointing, because instead of being a 15-point
game, it was five points," Bird said. "We just wanted to stay
aggressive, which we were."

The Storm have won five of their last six against the Silver
Stars.
